**Key APIs:**
- `std::source_location::current()` as a default parameter captures call site at compile time.
- `std::throw_with_nested(e)` creates an exception that is both `e` and a `nested_exception`.
- `std::rethrow_if_nested(e)` peels back the chain — enables full stack reconstruction.

```cpp
#include <algorithm>
#include <utility>
#include <cstddef>
#include <print>

class Buffer {
    int* data_;
    std::size_t size_;

public:
    explicit Buffer(std::size_t n)
        : data_(new int[n]()), size_(n) {}

    // Copy constructor — strong exception guarantee
    Buffer(const Buffer& other)
        : data_(new int[other.size_]), size_(other.size_) {
        std::copy_n(other.data_, size_, data_);
    }

    // Move constructor — noexcept, no allocation
    Buffer(Buffer&& other) noexcept
        : data_(std::exchange(other.data_, nullptr))
        , size_(std::exchange(other.size_, 0)) {}

    // Copy-and-swap: single assignment operator handles both copy and move
    // Exception safety: if copy ctor throws, *this is unchanged
    Buffer& operator=(Buffer other) noexcept { // pass by value = copy or move
        swap(*this, other); // noexcept swap
        return *this;
        // other's destructor frees old data
    }

    friend void swap(Buffer& a, Buffer& b) noexcept {
        using std::swap;
        swap(a.data_, b.data_);
        swap(a.size_, b.size_);
    }

    ~Buffer() { delete[] data_; }

    std::size_t size() const noexcept { return size_; }
    int& operator[](std::size_t i) { return data_[i]; }
};

int main() {
    Buffer a(10), b(20);
    a[0] = 99;

    b = a;            // copy assignment — strong guarantee
    b = std::move(a); // move assignment — noexcept

    std::println("b[0] = {}, size = {}", b[0], b.size()); // 99, 10

    Buffer c = b;     // copy constructor
    std::println("c[0] = {}", c[0]); // 99
}
```

**Exception safety levels:**
- **Basic:** No leak, object in valid (possibly changed) state.
- **Strong:** If exception thrown, state is unchanged (transactional).
- **Nothrow:** Never throws — `noexcept` functions.

**Copy-and-swap provides strong guarantee:** The copy happens before any mutation. If the copy throws, `*this` is never modified. The swap is `noexcept`, so after a successful copy, the assignment always succeeds.

```cpp
#include <atomic>
#include <array>
#include <thread>
#include <optional>
#include <print>

// Hazard pointers: each thread publishes which pointers it's using.
// Before freeing a node, check that no thread has it hazarded.
// This prevents use-after-free without garbage collection.

template<typename T, int MaxThreads = 8>
class HazardPointerDomain {
    struct HazardRecord {
        alignas(64) std::atomic<T*> ptr{nullptr};
    };

    std::array<HazardRecord, MaxThreads> records_;
    static thread_local int thread_id_;
    static int next_id_;

public:
    // Acquire a hazard pointer — publish intent to use ptr
    T* protect(std::atomic<T*>& src) {
        T* ptr;
        do {
            ptr = src.load(std::memory_order_acquire);
            records_[get_tid()].ptr.store(ptr, std::memory_order_release);
            // Re-read: if ptr changed between load and publish, retry
        } while (ptr != src.load(std::memory_order_acquire));
        return ptr;
    }

    void clear() {
        records_[get_tid()].ptr.store(nullptr, std::memory_order_release);
    }

    bool is_hazarded(T* ptr) const {
        for (auto& rec : records_)
            if (rec.ptr.load(std::memory_order_acquire) == ptr)
                return true;
        return false;
    }

    // Safe reclaim: only delete if no thread protects ptr
    void reclaim(T* ptr) {
        if (!is_hazarded(ptr))
            delete ptr;
        // Else: add to deferred list, retry later
    }

private:
    int get_tid() {
        if (thread_id_ == -1) thread_id_ = next_id_++;
        return thread_id_;
    }
};

template<typename T, int N> thread_local int HazardPointerDomain<T,N>::thread_id_ = -1;
template<typename T, int N> int HazardPointerDomain<T,N>::next_id_ = 0;
```

**Why hazard pointers are needed:**
In a lock-free stack, thread A loads `head` = ptr, gets preempted. Thread B pops and **frees** ptr. Thread A resumes and dereferences freed memory.

**Protocol:**
1. Thread publishes pointer in hazard record (`protect`).
2. Re-reads source to confirm pointer didn't change under us.
3. Before freeing: scan all records. If any thread has the pointer, defer the free.

**Alternatives:** Epoch-based reclamation (RCU), `shared_ptr` (expensive), quiescent-state-based reclamation. Hazard pointers are deterministic and O(N) to scan.

